<p>Certainly! Here are two innovative vegetarian lunch recipes that blend traditional French
  techniques with a modern, molecular gastronomy twist:</p>
<p><strong>1. Truffle-infused Mushroom Risotto Spheres:</strong></p>
<p><strong>Ingredients:</strong></p>
<ul>
  <li>Arborio rice</li>
  <li>Assorted mushrooms (shiitake, oyster, and porcini)</li>
  <li>Truffle oil</li>
  <li>Vegetable broth</li>
  <li>Parmesan cheese</li>
  <li>Shallots and garlic</li>
  <li>White wine</li>
  <li>Olive oil</li>
  <li>Fresh chives for garnish</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Instructions:</strong></p>
<ol>
  <li>Sauté finely chopped shallots and garlic in olive oil until translucent.</li>
  <li>Add Arborio rice and toast until it becomes slightly golden.</li>
  <li>Deglaze with white wine, allowing it to absorb into the rice.</li>
  <li>Begin adding warm vegetable broth gradually, stirring constantly until the rice is cooked al
    dente.</li>
  <li>In a separate pan, sauté assorted mushrooms in truffle oil until tender and aromatic.</li>
  <li>Fold the mushrooms into the risotto along with freshly grated Parmesan cheese.</li>
  <li>Allow the risotto to cool slightly, then shape it into small spheres using a mold.</li>
  <li>Serve the truffle-infused mushroom risotto spheres garnished with finely chopped chives.</li>
</ol>
<p><strong>2. Ratatouille Napoleon with Basil Foam:</strong></p>
<p><strong>Ingredients:</strong></p>
<ul>
  <li>Zucchini</li>
  <li>Eggplant</li>
  <li>Bell peppers (red, yellow, and green)</li>
  <li>Tomatoes</li>
  <li>Olive oil</li>
  <li>Garlic</li>
  <li>Thyme and rosemary</li>
  <li>Salt and pepper</li>
  <li>Fresh basil leaves</li>
  <li>Agar-agar powder</li>
  <li>Soy lecithin</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Instructions:</strong></p>
<ol>
  <li>Thinly slice zucchini, eggplant, bell peppers, and tomatoes.</li>
  <li>Sauté each vegetable separately with garlic, thyme, and rosemary until tender.</li>
  <li>Assemble the Ratatouille Napoleon by layering the vegetables and drizzling each layer with olive
    oil.</li>
  <li>Bake until the vegetables are cooked through and have a slightly crispy texture.</li>
  <li>For the basil foam, blend fresh basil leaves with water and strain the liquid.</li>
  <li>Heat the basil liquid, add agar-agar, and bring to a boil. Let it cool slightly.</li>
  <li>Use a hand blender to froth the basil mixture, incorporating soy lecithin for stability.</li>
  <li>Spoon the basil foam over the Ratatouille Napoleon just before serving.</li>
</ol>
<p>Feel free to experiment with these recipes, and remember that presentation is key! Enjoy your
  culinary adventure!</p>